(15, 3, 'Family Law', 'Mutual Consent Divorce', 'family-law', 'Divorce , types of Divorce , Mutual Consent Divorce', 'Divorce , types of Divorce , Mutual Consent Divorce, Section 13B of Hindu Marriage Act 1955', '<h1><strong>TYPES OF DIVORCE</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>MUTUAL CONSENT DIVORCE-</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>There are separate statutes under which Mutual Consent Divorce May be filed depending upon under which Act one is governed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Section <strong>13B of the Hindu Marriage Act ,1955</strong>&nbsp; for Hindus, Sikhs , jains etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Section 28 of Special Marriage Act 1954</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also Under <strong>Section 10A in THE DIVORCE ACT, 1869</strong> for Christians-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Mutual consent divorce is the&nbsp; fastest and probably the easiest possible manner parties can dissolve their marriage . A mutual consent divorce can be filed when&nbsp; both&nbsp; parties have mutually agreed to settle their disputes / claims whatsoever.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>In the case of those governed under the Indian divorce Act 1869 i.e Christians there should be 2 years separation prior to filing the divorce petition . In other cases its 1 year separation prior to filing the mutual consent divorce petition.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>What are the Grounds for filing Mutual Consent Divorce?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Only ground is Temperamental Differences which means no allegations againt one another.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Where is a Mutual consent Divorce Petition Filed ?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Since it&rsquo;s a Mutually agreed Petition its filed as a joint petition before the Court of the Principal Judge ,Family Court</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>How long does it take to file the Joint Petition?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Drafting of Mutual consent Joint Petition takes one day to draft as there are no allegations against each other.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>What is the Jurisdiction to file a Mutual Consent Divorce Petition?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>The Joint Petition can be filed where the parties last resided together or where the wife resides at present or where the marriage was solemnized?</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>How many times do the parties have to appear in court for&nbsp; hearing?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>After filing of the joint petition , court will provide date for the first hearing which is usually within a week to 15 days depends on which city you reside in , in some places it&rsquo;s the same day filing and same day appearance for first motion hearing. Once the hearing is over there will be a cooling period of 6 months and thereafter parties appear as and when the date is given for second motion hearing.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>In Delhi one has to file a second motion petition separately . In most other cities and even in Gurugram, Greater Noida , Faridabad , Ghaziabad a next date is given so one does not have to file a separate second motion petition.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>What should you prepare for the hearings?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Two most important things usually asked are date of marriage and date of separation . It is the discretion of the Court to satisfy it self with other questions on why do you want to dissolve your marriage ? etc .</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Can we get the second motion hearing done before 6 months?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Yes , You may file a waiver application in case the date of separation is more than 18 months.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>How long do we wait after the second motion hearing is over ?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Once the hearing for second motion is over and the court allows your divorce it is just a matter of time you will be handed over your divorce decree and that&rsquo;s the final dissolution of marriage certificate as you may call it.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>You may call at <strong>9873628941</strong> for any issue related to filing Mutual Consent Divorce Petition .</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1><strong>CONTESTED DIVORCE</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<h3>Contested Divorce is filed when one party files a divorce petition against another on any of the grounds mentioned herein under</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>One&nbsp; filed a contested divorce on any one or more grounds mentioned in Section 13 in The Hindu Marriage Act, 1955&nbsp; in case of Hindus.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>Most common grounds under which a contested divorce is filed under Section 13&nbsp; Hindu Marriage Act 1955 are the following:</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>(1) Any marriage solemnised, whether before or after the commencement of this Act, may, on a petition presented by either the husband or the wife, be dissolved by a decree of divorce on the ground that the other party</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;[(i) has, after the solemnisation of the marriage, had voluntary sexual intercourse with any person other than his or her spouse; or]</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;[(ia) has, after the solemnisation of the marriage, treated the petitioner with cruelty; or&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;[(ib) has deserted the petitioner for a continuous period of not less than two years immediately preceding the presentation of the petition; or]</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Cruelty - </strong>This is a common ground and it could either be mental cruelty or Physical Cruelty</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Desertion-&nbsp; Living separately for a continuous period of 2 years of more.</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>FAMILY COURT - POWER TO GRANT DIVORCE&nbsp;</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;Family Court does no have power to grant divorce on the ground&nbsp; on the ground of irretrievable&nbsp; breakdown of marriage only because there is a long separation . Family court cannot&nbsp; exercise such powers&nbsp; which are&nbsp; not conferred on the Family Court by the Act. Family Courts have to restrict&nbsp; and consider&nbsp; the parameters of the provision of grant of divorce strictly in accordance with the Act. Irretrievable breakdown of marriage is not a ground got&nbsp; divorcr under the Act.</h3>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n', '1.png', 'banner_article16.jpg', 2),
(16, 3, 'Arbitration', '', 'arbitration', '', '', '<p>In family arbitration you and your partner appoint an Arbitrator to make a decision (using the law that applies in England &amp; Wales) on any financial and property issues arising from the breakdown of your relationship that you have not been able to reach agreement on. The Arbitrator will make a decision that will be final and binding between you. Family arbitration was developed to enable couples going through family breakdown to resolve financial disputes more quickly, confidentially and in a more flexible and less formal setting than a courtroom. This flexibility and the fact that you will get a final decision much more quickly can make arbitration more cost-effective than court. Pauline Purcell is an Arbitrator and can therefore undertake matters on this basis. Please contact Pauline Purcell for further information.</p>\r\n', '2.png', 'arbitration-banner_2256_3515.jpg', 2),
